posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>17420550
>Armaf Niche Oud
Ambery, warm frag. There are some spices but I can't really detect them. Supposedly a clone of Ambre Sultan, although I haven't tried it. The drydown reminds me a bit of Bentley for Men Intense, although I get an incensey church vibe from it. Very good longevity and great sillage for hours. I just have a decant and I still haven't finished it in over a year. Just 1-3 sprays is more than enough.
>Mancera Sahara Wind
Leathery, slightly spicy, soapy. Reminds me of a old man's shaving soap in a good way. Less projection and longevity but still above average to me.
>Kenzo Jungle
Fresh, woody/spicy frag, a little powdery to my nose. I get a note that I can't really explain (could be the mate or guaiac wood) which I haven't really smelled before but it does smell nice. Decent for warm weather but I've never worn it on a very hot day. This is the lightest frag in terms of projection but still a decent performer and does last a long time on my skin, although I go heavier on the sprays.

NTA but a quick google search shows that the originak breton shirts date from the mid 19th century and had 21 stripes, one for each Napoleon victory. They were worn by sailors because it made them easier to spot if they fell overboard. Later, Coco Chanel used the design in some of her stuff.

>How do I make sure it’s genuine
By doing a lot of research and getting to know the brand and the watches they produced. Seikos for instance all have their reference number on the dial under the 6 o'clock marker and you can work from there.
>what should I usually ask the seller?
Just basic stuff, photos help a ton.
>Should I get a pic of the mechanism?
Not that important, it matters more whether it has been serviced recently or not.
>What should I expect from an accuracy stand point.
Not much to be honest. Mechanical watches, especially older ones, aren't that accurate to begin with, generally they can be brought down to around +/- a minute per day i would say, that i would consider acceptable. I haven't checked mine yet because i rarely wear them.

>>17419642
The Germans mainly make three types of watches very well; tool/pilot, Bauhaus and the traditional marine watches.
They tend to be a bit more rough around the edges, simplistic and don't have the sleek elegance of the swiss.
It can also be a bit of an acquired taste for the German quirkiness in some cases.
Most cheap brands use same or similar off the shelf movements or modify them in the upper price ranges. Typically you have to go above 5k to find in-house movements, unless you shop vintage of course.

Sinn make some of the coolest and most unique tool watches in my opinion, at an affordable price. Use a few meme features normal people don't need that drives up price and service cost. Helmut Sinn was himself a fighter pilot in WW2.

Nomos get hate for being leftist faggots, but I can't hate on their designs even though I'm not a fan of Bauhaus. They also make traditional watches for us wristlets that don't like +40mm dinner plates that the Germans seems to be fond of. May also be an exception for cheapish in-house movements, not sure where they start at.

Stowa, Laco and Hanhart mainly live off their legacy as makers of WW2 watches, uses off the shelf movements and sadly aren't real watch makers anymore. Affordable and good looking though.

Glashütte Original, the poor man's Lange, is a high end vertically integrated manufacturer, (almost) on par with JLC, although, certainly not as accomplished.
They have some pretty cool designs. You can usually find early 2000s designs at a decent price on chrono24.

It's kind of funny. They have modernist Bauhaus designs and the design department is located in the degenerate hell hole known as Berlin. Yet, they're the vanguard of German watch making. Independent and not owned by a conglomerate, unlike A Lange and Glashütte Original. Developed their own complete movements.

>In 2013, Nomos debuted a line of calibres called the DUW line – short for Deutsche Uhrenwekre. All of this led up to the release of a proprietary swing system in 2014. This didn’t happen all at once. The new swing system had been in development since 2007, and had required a partnership with TU Dresden, as well as an investment of 12 million euros.

>The main challenge of producing a swing system is that it requires incredible skill and precision. The pallet, escape wheel, and balance, along with the other parts, have to be produced with micrometer-level precision. Not only do they have to be produced with this level of precision, but they have to work in tandem. Uwe Ahrendt, the general manager who oversaw the process and is now CEO, compared the process of producing a new swing system to landing on the moon.

>This is the reason most watch manufacturers either buy someone else’s movement, or produce an in-house movement based on an existing movement. Simply put, engineering a new swing system from scratch is both too expensive and too demanding a task for most watch manufacturers to afford. To this day, only a handful of highly-skilled Nomos watchmakers are qualified to manufacture them. Hence the continued dominance of Swiss calibres like ETA. Much like the moon landing was a “giant leap for mankind”, producing an in-house swing system was a giant leap for Nomos. It allowed them to create their own watches entirely from scratch, without relying on any other firms to produce their parts.

well I am almost done building these 2 test plates. Some hasguns offered to shoot them for me. Results should come soon. They're build like the armor, rigid, laminated with epoxy. Which gives me an idea to make a third test panel, consisting of only 12 layers of the thinner fibreglass, without any adherement.

About aramid, it's 10 times as expensive compared to various different types of fibreglass. Fibreglass comes in different weaves and weights per m2. I used two types, a heavy kind called woven roving, large strands weighing about 500 - 800 g/m2 (ebay descriptions are always a bit iffy) and a light, tightly woven glass weighing in on 160 - 240 or so g/m2. 10m2 of either of that stuff costs about 30€, aramid in that quantity around 300€+.

Depends on how worn in they are, but yeah, you're generally fine getting them used since the heat from your foot will just mold the leather to a new shape.
As for things to look out for, pay attention to the quality of the uppers ( thick full grain leather, no loose grain, no cracks), look for a stitched on sole (leather, vibram, or dainite), and look for a leather footbed.
It might be good to go to a high end store or a place that specializes in boots to get a feel for quality so you know what to look for as well

posts.com:
SOTD was Montebaco Verano.
You know what, this fragrance sucks. Not because it's bad or anything, it sucks because I smelled Intensivo first. Verano is more mass appealing, smooth and sweet. Intensivo is rougher but more nuanced and interesting .

In Verano the leather is neutered, the tea is gone, the florals are gone, the tobacco is softer, there's no sexy musk smells. What's left is a very appealing cashmeran , suede and grapefruit bomb that smells wonderful but not as artistic as Intensivo.
Basically Intensivo cost more but I didn't mind paying it because I got a genuine niche fragrance that was evocative of what it claimed in the ads and reviews. Verano "perfects" this by smoothing out all the rough edges and being sweeter and more airy, it's niche filtered through designer sensibility.

It's not bad, in fact if I smelled it first I would have loved it. But Intensivo is a 10/10, Verano is a 7 that would have been a 9 if I didn't already wear Intensivo

posts.com:
Wore 1986 Eclectique by Les Baines Guerbois and today. So happy I bought a bottle. I know high praise for a fragrance on these threads normally reeks of hyperbole or fake hype but it's one of my favorites, I bought a bottle after blowing up through a decant.
If you're a young dude who's still into sweet frags and light blue scents, that's awesome but this isn't going to be your bag. I'm middle aged, this is a perfect romantic/date night fragrance for me.
This will sound crazy but the 1986 smells like a bar, and multiple people wearing different fragrances inside the bar, but in a good way. There's a boozy rum cocktail smell, aged rum and red and stone fruits, plus the smell of the barrel itself. There's the smell of fresh tobacco, smells just like how opening a fresh pack of Marlboro reds used to smell. There's a faint leather smell like a well worn jacket. And then there's combinations of notes that my brain reads as other distinct fragrances. There's a strong myrrh note, combined with patchouli and amber and it smells exactly like the drydown of Prada Amber Homme intense. Then there's a strong musk, vanilla and oakmoss combo that smells like the drydown of a typical barbershop fragrance, but I'm picking this up at the same time as the Prada smell, and all of them together with the boozy bar and tobacco smell.
But it doesn't smell disjointed or unnatural, it smells like walking past two people in a bar wearing fragrances the smell nice and somehow it all smells nice together.
Most fragrances smell nice, it's rare to find one that displays such imagination to come up with a concept and the technical mastery to execute the idea.
I know what I'm saying probably sounds nuts, that's fine. I'm not saying go buy a bottle, it's expensive, don't waste your money. I am encouraging you to get a sample and experience something very different than what's currently on the market, and I hope you love it like I do

SOTD: Origins of the Collector

I absolutely despise the faggy ass name of this house and this fragrance because it smells so damn good that I know people are going to ask about it and I'm going to look like a retard explaining it.
I'll keep my review shorter than previous ones because apparently reading hurts (you) anons. Opening it a blast of bitter coffee grinds joined in by a sharp slightly smoky olibanum aka frankincense. Had the fragrance stayed in this lane I would love it more but it would be way more challenging to wear. Things quickly settle down and the black coffee grounds because Starbucks coffee with caramal sweetener. The incense calms down and takes on a slight dark fruit tinge but the coffee is the start of the show here. It doesn't evolve much after that but it doesn't need to, fragrances like this are non-existent in the designer realm and still rare in niche. If you're familiar with Rochas Man and New Haarlem you'll understand the coffee smell here. This fragrance isn't as sweeter as those however, Origins is 60% coffee and 40% incense+spice.
Longevity is great. Projection is explosive for the first hour then gently weakens over the day.

I can't imagine wearing this in temps above 60, it has such a cold weather character to it that it would be wasteful to wear this in heat. Maybe spring date nights when the weather is cool.
Overall, great frag, easy 8.5-9/10

Recommended smelling: Rochas Man and New Haarlem are the two obvious choices. If you want a challenging and slightly animalic coffee try Eau des Iles

https://www.fragrantica.com/perfume/Maitre-Parfumeur-et-Gantier/Eau-des-Iles-5601.html

If you want a slightly sweeter and more pure coffee scent,try Coffee Addict. This is a far safer choice than Origin, but if you love the smell of coffee and want to smell like it all day this is one of the few coffee scents with good longevity

https://www.fragrantica.com/perfume/Theodoros-Kalotinis/Coffee-Addict-64660.html

>>17420104
IMHO one of the best conceptual executions of being a flanker I've ever seen. To me most flankers are soulless cash grabs that tweak something very slightly and expect you to pay full price for it (Le Male flankers) or they smell nothing like the original and are just copying a proven name because the company is unsure it would succeed as a new IP (Sauvage Elixir).

Extreme is brilliant though. It clearly references the original but then goes in enough of a new direction that it justifies the purchase even if you own the original EN. Instead of a vetiver bomb the fragrance is many 30-40% the original EN and the rest is a bone dry incense and cypress. The color of the fragrance really works and matches the smell, it's autumnal and golden, arrid brown.

The other EN Sport flanker is great as a flanker too, it's concerts the inky stygian darkness of the original EN into something that's still clearly EN but also works on a summer day.

Lalique as a company is massively under hyped. All of their fragrances smell good and are unique in some way, they don't have an clear cash grabs, and the price to value ratio is amazing even on their price/luxe offerings. But they aren't normiecore like Versace, Ralph Lauren or Paco Rabanne. They aren't insanely expensive and rare enough to appeal to the snobs and their marketing department doesn't buy YouTube hype so they don't appeal to the Jeremy Fragrance pajeet incel demographic. Naturally no one talks about Lalique here either besides Encre Noir which is their most well known scent. It's a shame.

posts.com:
>>17412632
>>17412667
For a 1st time home job + by yourself it looks pretty good. If a pro did it i world demand money back, but thats spending $300 not $15 sooo....
Notes:
You will be shocked how different it looks toned re: white, get some purple in asap (warning, you want the 1st few days to look purple tinged to get good white)
If you are going to bleach again give it a few weeks + high intensity repair products, otherwise your hair will be even more giga bleach fucked (this is from 1 thin hair mf to another).
From here you are going to need to use a surprising amount of leave in conditioners and shit. Go sulfate free too. Dont just hope it will be fine, your hair is so thin its going to be weak af and break and start looking noticeable less + frizzy/splitendy
(Also, potentially the best non olaplex product ive ever used is too cool for school egg mask)

You obvs did it in a cold room or had less heat etc on the ends because they are so much darker. In the same vein Id be worried that the base of the hairs are overprocessed and are going to be brittle since you obvs didnt balance times (against scalp processes faster due to heat). Next time will be hard because you need to do the roots, but also completely avoid the previous base since it would be overprocessed already.

Honestly, i know its expensive, but bleaching really is something pros do better. You can pull off 1 time yourself, but when it then comes to blending new growth in and evening it out band free any shitty or at home jobs makes it that much harder.
There is a reason that colour correction is more expensive than just plain bleaching, its to even out and fix up all the prev flaws and takes much much longer than just doing it well to begin with.
